# to make life easier
import pandas as pd

di1 = pd.Index(dockI_2018_05_18)
di2 = pd.Index(dockI_2018_05_21)
di3 = pd.Index(dockI_2018_06_17)
di4 = pd.Index(dockI_2018_07_10)
di5 = pd.Index(dockI_2018_07_14)

dockIs = (('2018_05_18',di1), ('2018_05_21',di2), ('2018_06_17',di3), ('2018_07_10',di4), ('2018_07_14',di5))

for d in dockIs:
    print("{} has {} packages".format(d[0], len(d[1])))

for k in range( len(dockIs) - 1 ):
    temp = list( dockIs[k][1].difference( dockIs[k+1][1] ) )

package_name = 'Fiona' # (case sensitive)

    temp = d[1].searchsorted(package_name) # it's not 100% trustworthy :(

# to get a list of packages installed in a specific date-time stamp (determined by docker images)
import pkg_resources

dist = [d for d in pkg_resources.working_set] # The directory

sd = [] # dist items as strings
for d in dist:
    sd.append(str(d))
sd.sort()
